  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Nutrition and Health Response in 12 Drought-affected Hotspot Priority Woredas in West Arsi, (Adaba, Arsi Negele, Shamane zuria, Wondo, and  Shalla), East Shewa  (Adami Tulu Jido Kombolcha, East Hararghe (Gola Oda), and North Shewa (Dara, Degem,  W/Jarso and Wuchale)  zones of Oromia Region and Offa woreda/Wolayita of SNNPR in Ethiopia.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IMC has been responding to the needs of vulnerable communities in West Arsi, East Showa and East Haraghe zone targeted woredas in Oromia region.  The targeted community has been affected with critical food insecurity due to the 2015 Belg rain failure and irregularities of the 2015 Meher rain both in intensity and duration. The current HRF project in these zones targeting seven woredas will end on April 20, 2016. However, the situation on the ground has not changed much due to the drought and delayed 2016 Belg rain. The situation on the ground necessitates extending the support in the seven woredas.  Moreover, IMC conducted rapid assessment in Norh shewa zone from March 23-25/2016 and Offa woreda of Wolayita from April 13-14, 2016 to measure the demanding needs in 12 woredas. The findings indicate the food security situation is rapidly deteriorating and it is expected to worsen as the current Belg performance is poor coupled with almost complete failure of the Meher production. The screening shows sharp increase in malnutrition in target woredas namely: Dara, Degem, W/Jarso and Wuchale compared to the previous months. Labor migration is becoming coping strategy there is an effort by the government authority to address the existing needs although there are still areas to fill the gap.  The situation in Offa is the same as complete belg and meher crop failure reported from woreda DPPO for the major livelihood crops. In response to the existing gaps, IMC is planning to support local efforts by providing technical and logistical support to target four woredas in North Shewa and one woreda in Wolayita (Offa) to implement CMAM and public health emergency response. This project is intended to benefit mainly PLW&#x2019;s and children under five. The main activities includes, training government staff on SAM and MAM management, providing logistical support for procurement of essential drugs and materials and strengthening public health emergency management at community level.</narrative>
  </description>
